-- JOHN CHAPTER 8 — The Light of the World and the Great I AM
-- 59 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 8,
  'John 8 contains some of the most dramatic confrontations and exalted christological claims in the entire Gospel. The chapter opens with the Pericope Adulterae (vv.1-11), the story of the woman taken in adultery — ''He that is without sin among you, let him first cast a stone at her'' (v.7). Though absent from the earliest Greek manuscripts, the passage has been treasured by the church as authentic tradition. Beginning at v.12, Jesus continues teaching at the Feast of Tabernacles, now making his second great ''I AM'' declaration: ''I am the light of the world: he that followeth me shall not walk in darkness, but shall have the light of life'' (v.12). This claim, made during the festival''s lamplight ceremony, is staggering — Jesus claims to be what the great candelabra in the temple court merely symbolised. The Pharisees challenge his self-testimony (v.13), and Jesus responds by asserting dual witness: ''I am one that bear witness of myself, and the Father that sent me beareth witness of me'' (v.18). The discourse escalates through a series of increasingly confrontational exchanges. Jesus warns: ''I go my way, and ye shall seek me, and shall die in your sins: whither I go, ye cannot come'' (v.21). ''If ye believe not that I am he, ye shall die in your sins'' (v.24). He promises genuine freedom to those who believe: ''If ye continue in my word, then are ye my disciples indeed; And ye shall know the truth, and the truth shall make you free'' (vv.31-32). The Jews protest that they are Abraham''s children; Jesus counters that their works prove otherwise: ''Ye are of your father the devil, and the lusts of your father ye will do'' (v.44). The confrontation reaches its climax with the supreme christological claim: ''Verily, verily, I say unto you, Before Abraham was, I am'' (v.58). This absolute ''I AM'' (egō eimi) is a direct claim to the divine name revealed at the burning bush (Exodus 3:14). The Jews understand perfectly and take up stones to kill him for blasphemy (v.59).',
  'The Light of the World — Freedom, Truth, and the Divine I AM',
  'ἐγώ εἰμι (egō eimi)',
  'I AM — the absolute self-designation of Jesus that echoes the divine name revealed to Moses at the burning bush: ''I AM THAT I AM'' (Exodus 3:14, Hebrew: ehyeh asher ehyeh, LXX: egō eimi ho ōn). In John 8, egō eimi is used in its most absolute and confrontational form. In v.24, ''if ye believe not that I am (egō eimi), ye shall die in your sins.'' In v.28, ''when ye have lifted up the Son of man, then shall ye know that I am (egō eimi).'' In v.58, ''Before Abraham was, I am (egō eimi)'' — not ''I was'' (past tense) but ''I am'' (present tense), claiming eternal, timeless existence. The Jews'' immediate reaction — picking up stones to stone him (v.59) — proves they understood this as a claim to deity, not merely a claim to pre-existence.',
  '["The Woman Taken in Adultery (vv.1-11): Jesus went unto the mount of Olives. Early in the morning he came again into the temple and all the people came unto him and he sat down and taught them. The scribes and Pharisees brought unto him a woman taken in adultery and set her in the midst. They say unto him Master this woman was taken in adultery in the very act. Now Moses in the law commanded us that such should be stoned but what sayest thou? This they said tempting him that they might have to accuse him. But Jesus stooped down and with his finger wrote on the ground. When they continued asking him he lifted up himself and said He that is without sin among you let him first cast a stone at her. And again he stooped down and wrote on the ground. They which heard it being convicted by their own conscience went out one by one beginning at the eldest even unto the last and Jesus was left alone and the woman standing in the midst. Jesus said unto her Woman where are those thine accusers? Hath no man condemned thee? She said No man Lord. And Jesus said Neither do I condemn thee go and sin no more","I Am the Light of the World (vv.12-20): Then spake Jesus again unto them saying I am the light of the world he that followeth me shall not walk in darkness but shall have the light of life. The Pharisees therefore said unto him Thou bearest record of thyself thy record is not true. Jesus answered and said unto them Though I bear record of myself yet my record is true for I know whence I came and whither I go but ye cannot tell whence I come and whither I go. Ye judge after the flesh I judge no man. And yet if I judge my judgment is true for I am not alone but I and the Father that sent me. It is also written in your law that the testimony of two men is true. I am one that bear witness of myself and the Father that sent me beareth witness of me. Then said they unto him Where is thy Father? Jesus answered Ye neither know me nor my Father — if ye had known me ye should have known my Father also. These words spake Jesus in the treasury as he taught in the temple and no man laid hands on him for his hour was not yet come","Ye Shall Die in Your Sins (vv.21-30): Then said Jesus again unto them I go my way and ye shall seek me and shall die in your sins whither I go ye cannot come. Then said the Jews Will he kill himself? because he saith Whither I go ye cannot come. And he said unto them Ye are from beneath I am from above ye are of this world I am not of this world. I said therefore unto you that ye shall die in your sins for if ye believe not that I am he ye shall die in your sins. Then said they unto him Who art thou? And Jesus saith unto them Even the same that I said unto you from the beginning. I have many things to say and to judge of you but he that sent me is true and I speak to the world those things which I have heard of him. They understood not that he spake to them of the Father. Then said Jesus unto them When ye have lifted up the Son of man then shall ye know that I am he and that I do nothing of myself but as my Father hath taught me I speak these things. And he that sent me is with me the Father hath not left me alone for I do always those things that please him. As he spake these words many believed on him","The Truth Shall Make You Free (vv.31-38): Then said Jesus to those Jews which believed on him If ye continue in my word then are ye my disciples indeed And ye shall know the truth and the truth shall make you free. They answered him We be Abraham''s seed and were never in bondage to any man how sayest thou Ye shall be made free? Jesus answered them Verily verily I say unto you Whosoever committeth sin is the servant of sin. And the servant abideth not in the house for ever but the Son abideth ever. If the Son therefore shall make you free ye shall be free indeed. I know that ye are Abraham''s seed but ye seek to kill me because my word hath no place in you. I speak that which I have seen with my Father and ye do that which ye have seen with your father","Children of Abraham or Children of the Devil (vv.39-47): They answered and said unto him Abraham is our father. Jesus saith unto them If ye were Abraham''s children ye would do the works of Abraham. But now ye seek to kill me a man that hath told you the truth which I have heard of God this did not Abraham. Ye do the deeds of your father. Then said they to him We be not born of fornication we have one Father even God. Jesus said unto them If God were your Father ye would love me for I proceeded forth and came from God neither came I of myself but he sent me. Why do ye not understand my speech? even because ye cannot hear my word. Ye are of your father the devil and the lusts of your father ye will do. He was a murderer from the beginning and abode not in the truth because there is no truth in him. When he speaketh a lie he speaketh of his own for he is a liar and the father of it. And because I tell you the truth ye believe me not. Which of you convinceth me of sin? And if I say the truth why do ye not believe me? He that is of God heareth God''s words ye therefore hear them not because ye are not of God","Before Abraham Was I AM (vv.48-59): Then answered the Jews and said unto him Say we not well that thou art a Samaritan and hast a devil? Jesus answered I have not a devil but I honour my Father and ye do dishonour me. And I seek not mine own glory there is one that seeketh and judgeth. Verily verily I say unto you If a man keep my saying he shall never see death. Then said the Jews unto him Now we know that thou hast a devil. Abraham is dead and the prophets and thou sayest If a man keep my saying he shall never taste of death. Art thou greater than our father Abraham which is dead? and the prophets are dead whom makest thou thyself? Jesus answered If I honour myself my honour is nothing it is my Father that honoureth me of whom ye say that he is your God. Yet ye have not known him but I know him and if I should say I know him not I shall be a liar like unto you but I know him and keep his saying. Your father Abraham rejoiced to see my day and he saw it and was glad. Then said the Jews unto him Thou art not yet fifty years old and hast thou seen Abraham? Jesus said unto them Verily verily I say unto you Before Abraham was I am. Then took they up stones to cast at him but Jesus hid himself and went out of the temple going through the midst of them and so passed by"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'John';

-- Step 2: Insert all 59 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'Jesus went unto the mount of Olives.',
   'Ἰησοῦς δὲ ἐπορεύθη εἰς τὸ ὄρος τῶν ἐλαιῶν',
   'Iēsous de eporeuthē eis to oros tōn elaiōn',
   'The Pericope Adulterae (7:53-8:11) is absent from the earliest and best Greek manuscripts (P66, P75, Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and likely was not part of John''s original text. However, the story is widely considered historically authentic — it bears the marks of genuine tradition and was preserved by the church. ''The mount of Olives'' (to oros tōn elaiōn) — Jesus often retreated there (Luke 21:37; 22:39). While ''every man went unto his own house'' (7:53), Jesus had no permanent home (Matthew 8:20).',
   NULL),
  (2, 'And early in the morning he came again into the temple, and all the people came unto him; and he sat down, and taught them.',
   'ὄρθρου δὲ πάλιν παρεγένετο εἰς τὸ ἱερὸν καὶ πᾶς ὁ λαὸς ἤρχετο πρὸς αὐτόν καὶ καθίσας ἐδίδασκεν αὐτούς',
   'orthrou de palin paregeneto eis to hieron kai pas ho laos ērcheto pros auton kai kathisas edidasken autous',
   '''Early in the morning'' (orthrou — at dawn). ''Sat down, and taught'' — the seated posture of authoritative teaching. ''All the people came'' — Jesus'' popularity with the common people is persistent despite the authorities'' opposition.',
   NULL),
  (3, 'And the scribes and Pharisees brought unto him a woman taken in adultery; and when they had set her in the midst,',
   'ἄγουσιν δὲ οἱ γραμματεῖς καὶ οἱ Φαρισαῖοι πρὸς αὐτὸν γυναῖκα ἐν μοιχείᾳ κατειλημμένην καὶ στήσαντες αὐτὴν ἐν μέσῳ',
   'agousin de hoi grammateis kai hoi Pharisaioi pros auton gynaika en moicheia kateilēmmenēn kai stēsantes autēn en mesō',
   '''Taken in adultery'' (en moicheia kateilēmmenēn — caught in the act of adultery). ''Set her in the midst'' — publicly exposed, humiliated. The absence of the man (who was equally guilty, Leviticus 20:10) reveals the trap''s true nature: they do not care about justice but about ensnaring Jesus.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'They say unto him, Master, this woman was taken in adultery, in the very act.',
   'λέγουσιν αὐτῷ Διδάσκαλε αὕτη ἡ γυνὴ κατελήφθη ἐπαυτοφώρῳ μοιχευομένη',
   'legousin autō Didaskale hautē hē gynē katelēphthē epautophōrō moicheuomenē',
   '''In the very act'' (epautophōrō — caught in the act itself, red-handed). The evidence is indisputable. But the situation is manufactured: for the woman to be ''caught in the very act,'' witnesses had to be watching, which suggests a set-up. The Pharisees use a real sinner as a pawn in their game against Jesus.',
   NULL),
  (5, 'Now Moses in the law commanded us, that such should be stoned: but what sayest thou?',
   'ἐν δὲ τῷ νόμῳ Μωϋσῆς ἡμῖν ἐνετείλατο τὰς τοιαύτας λιθοβολεῖσθαι σὺ οὖν τί λέγεις',
   'en de tō nomō Mōysēs hēmin eneteilato tas toiautas lithobolesthai sy oun ti legeis',
   'The reference is to Leviticus 20:10 and Deuteronomy 22:22-24 (stoning for adultery). The trap is a dilemma: if Jesus says ''Stone her,'' he contradicts his message of mercy and potentially violates Roman law (which reserved capital punishment for Rome). If he says ''Don''t stone her,'' he contradicts Moses and can be accused of disregarding the Law.',
   NULL),
  (6, 'This they said, tempting him, that they might have to accuse him. But Jesus stooped down, and with his finger wrote on the ground, as though he heard them not.',
   'τοῦτο δὲ ἔλεγον πειράζοντες αὐτόν ἵνα ἔχωσιν κατηγορεῖν αὐτοῦ ὁ δὲ Ἰησοῦς κάτω κύψας τῷ δακτύλῳ ἔγραφεν εἰς τὴν γῆν',
   'touto de elegon peirazontes auton hina echōsin katēgorein autou ho de Iēsous katō kypsas tō daktylō egraphen eis tēn gēn',
   '''Tempting him'' (peirazontes auton — testing him). ''Wrote on the ground'' (tō daktylō egraphen eis tēn gēn — with his finger wrote on the ground). What Jesus wrote is unknown — speculations include: their sins, the names of accusers, OT texts (Jeremiah 17:13: ''they that depart from me shall be written in the earth''). The act itself is significant: Jesus refuses to engage with their trap on their terms. The ''finger of God'' wrote the law on stone tablets (Exodus 31:18); now the finger of God writes on earth.',
   NULL),
  (7, 'So when they continued asking him, he lifted up himself, and said unto them, He that is without sin among you, let him first cast a stone at her.',
   'ὡς δὲ ἐπέμενον ἐρωτῶντες αὐτόν ἀνακύψας εἶπεν πρὸς αὐτούς Ὁ ἀναμάρτητος ὑμῶν πρῶτος τὸν λίθον ἐπ᾽ αὐτῇ βαλέτω',
   'hōs de epemenon erōtōntes auton anakupsas eipen pros autous Ho anamartētos hymōn prōtos ton lithon ep autē baletō',
   '''He that is without sin'' (ho anamartētos — the sinless one, the one without sin). ''Let him first cast a stone'' — Jesus does not deny the law''s validity but turns it into a mirror. Deuteronomy 17:7 required the witnesses to cast the first stones. By adding ''without sin,'' Jesus shifts the focus from the woman''s guilt (which is undeniable) to the accusers'' standing. They came to judge her; they end up judged. The response is devastating in its simplicity: it upholds the law, exposes hypocrisy, and extends mercy simultaneously.',
   NULL),
  (8, 'And again he stooped down, and wrote on the ground.',
   'καὶ πάλιν κάτω κύψας ἔγραφεν εἰς τὴν γῆν',
   'kai palin katō kupsas egraphen eis tēn gēn',
   'Jesus bends down again and writes — giving the accusers time and space to process his words without the pressure of his gaze. He does not watch them leave; he does not gloat. The silence and the writing are acts of mercy toward the accusers as well as toward the woman.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'And they which heard it, being convicted by their own conscience, went out one by one, beginning at the eldest, even unto the last: and Jesus was left alone, and the woman standing in the midst.',
   'οἱ δὲ ἀκούσαντες καὶ ὑπὸ τῆς συνειδήσεως ἐλεγχόμενοι ἐξήρχοντο εἷς καθ᾽ εἷς ἀρξάμενοι ἀπὸ τῶν πρεσβυτέρων ἕως τῶν ἐσχάτων καὶ κατελείφθη μόνος ὁ Ἰησοῦς καὶ ἡ γυνὴ ἐν μέσῳ ἑστῶσα',
   'hoi de akousantes kai hypo tēs syneidēseōs elenchomenoi exērchonto heis kath heis arxamenoi apo tōn presbyterōn heōs tōn eschatōn kai kateleiphthē monos ho Iēsous kai hē gynē en mesō hestōsa',
   '''Convicted by their own conscience'' (hypo tēs syneidēseōs elenchomenoi — being convicted/reproved by conscience). ''Beginning at the eldest'' (arxamenoi apo tōn presbyterōn — starting from the oldest) — the oldest, with the most sins to remember, leave first. ''Jesus was left alone, and the woman'' — the only one without sin and the one caught in sin remain together. Augustine: ''Two remained: misery and mercy (miseria et misericordia).''',
   NULL),
  (10, 'When Jesus had lifted up himself, and saw none but the woman, he said unto her, Woman, where are those thine accusers? hath no man condemned thee?',
   'ἀνακύψας δὲ ὁ Ἰησοῦς καὶ μηδένα θεασάμενος πλὴν τῆς γυναικός εἶπεν αὐτῇ Γύναι ποῦ εἰσιν ἐκεῖνοι οἱ κατήγοροί σου οὐδείς σε κατέκρινεν',
   'anakupsas de ho Iēsous kai mēdena theasamenos plēn tēs gynaikos eipen autē Gynai pou eisin ekeinoi hoi katēgoroi sou oudeis se katekrinen',
   '''Woman'' (gynai — a respectful address, cf. 2:4; 19:26). ''Where are those thine accusers?'' — the accusers have gone; without witnesses, the legal case collapses. ''Hath no man condemned thee?'' (oudeis se katekrinen — has no one passed sentence on you?). Jesus creates space for the woman to see the mercy that has been extended.',
   NULL),
  (11, 'She said, No man, Lord. And Jesus said unto her, Neither do I condemn thee: go, and sin no more.',
   'ἡ δὲ εἶπεν Οὐδείς κύριε εἶπεν δὲ αὐτῇ ὁ Ἰησοῦς Οὐδὲ ἐγώ σε κατακρίνω πορεύου καὶ μηκέτι ἁμάρτανε',
   'hē de eipen Oudeis kyrie eipen de autē ho Iēsous Oude egō se katakrinō poreuou kai mēketi hamartane',
   '''Neither do I condemn thee'' (oude egō se katakrinō — nor do I pass sentence on you). ''Go, and sin no more'' (poreuou kai mēketi hamartane — go, and from now on stop sinning). Jesus neither condones the sin nor condemns the sinner. He extends mercy (''neither do I condemn'') while demanding transformation (''sin no more''). This is grace: not the absence of moral standards but the presence of transforming love. Jesus is the only one qualified to cast the stone — and he chooses not to.',
   'This story illustrates the perfect balance of grace and truth (John 1:14, 17). Jesus does not lower the moral standard (sin is still sin); he does not excuse (''go and sin no more''); he does not condemn (''neither do I condemn thee''). The story shows how God deals with sinners: with compassion, without compromise, toward transformation. The woman is free from condemnation but not free to continue sinning. Mercy received must produce a changed life.'),
  (12, 'Then spake Jesus again unto them, saying, I am the light of the world: he that followeth me shall not walk in darkness, but shall have the light of life.',
   'πάλιν οὖν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς ἐλάλησεν λέγων Ἐγώ εἰμι τὸ φῶς τοῦ κόσμου ὁ ἀκολουθῶν ἐμοὶ οὐ μὴ περιπατήσῃ ἐν τῇ σκοτίᾳ ἀλλ᾽ ἕξει τὸ φῶς τῆς ζωῆς',
   'palin oun autois ho Iēsous elalēsen legōn Egō eimi to phōs tou kosmou ho akolouthōn emoi ou mē peripatēsē en tē skotia all hexei to phōs tēs zōēs',
   '''I am the light of the world'' (Egō eimi to phōs tou kosmou — the second great ''I AM'' predicate statement). During Tabernacles, four enormous candelabra were lit in the Court of Women, illuminating all of Jerusalem. Jesus claims to be the reality these lights merely symbolised. ''He that followeth me'' (ho akolouthōn emoi — the one who follows me; present participle: keeps following). ''Shall not walk in darkness'' (ou mē peripatēsē en tē skotia — emphatic: will absolutely never walk in darkness). ''The light of life'' (to phōs tēs zōēs — the light that gives life, the light that is life). Light and life are paired: as physical light enables physical life, so Christ the spiritual light enables spiritual life.',
   'This is the second of seven ''I AM'' predicate statements in John. The OT repeatedly describes God as light: ''The LORD is my light'' (Psalm 27:1). ''In thy light shall we see light'' (Psalm 36:9). ''The LORD shall be unto thee an everlasting light'' (Isaiah 60:19-20). Jesus claims this divine attribute for himself. The Tabernacles light ceremony celebrated the pillar of fire that guided Israel (Exodus 13:21); Jesus claims to be the true pillar of fire — the permanent divine presence that guides, illuminates, and gives life. Darkness in John is not merely absence of light but the realm of sin, ignorance, and death (1:5; 3:19; 12:35, 46).'),
  (13, 'The Pharisees therefore said unto him, Thou bearest record of thyself; thy record is not true.',
   'εἶπον οὖν αὐτῷ οἱ Φαρισαῖοι Σὺ περὶ σεαυτοῦ μαρτυρεῖς ἡ μαρτυρία σου οὐκ ἔστιν ἀληθής',
   'eipon oun autō hoi Pharisaioi Sy peri seautou martyreis hē martyria sou ouk estin alēthēs',
   'The Pharisees invoke the legal principle that self-testimony is insufficient (cf. Deuteronomy 19:15). This echoes 5:31, where Jesus himself said ''If I bear witness of myself, my witness is not true'' (in the sense of legally valid). They use his own statement against him — but Jesus now elevates the discussion to a different plane (v.14).',
   NULL),
  (14, 'Jesus answered and said unto them, Though I bear record of myself, yet my record is true: for I know whence I came, and whither I go; but ye cannot tell whence I come, and whither I go.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς καὶ εἶπεν αὐτοῖς Κἂν ἐγὼ μαρτυρῶ περὶ ἐμαυτοῦ ἀληθής ἐστιν ἡ μαρτυρία μου ὅτι οἶδα πόθεν ἦλθον καὶ ποῦ ὑπάγω ὑμεῖς δὲ οὐκ οἴδατε πόθεν ἔρχομαι ἢ ποῦ ὑπάγω',
   'apekrithē Iēsous kai eipen autois Kan egō martyrō peri emautou alēthēs estin hē martyria mou hoti oida pothen ēlthon kai pou hypagō hymeis de ouk oidate pothen erchomai ē pou hypagō',
   '''Though I bear record of myself, yet my record is true'' — not a contradiction of 5:31 but a deeper claim. In 5:31, Jesus acknowledged the legal convention; here he asserts that his testimony is inherently true regardless of convention because he alone knows his origin and destiny. ''I know whence I came and whither I go'' — from the Father and back to the Father (cf. 16:28). Their ignorance of his origin disqualifies their judgment.',
   NULL),
  (15, 'Ye judge after the flesh; I judge no man.',
   'ὑμεῖς κατὰ τὴν σάρκα κρίνετε ἐγὼ οὐ κρίνω οὐδένα',
   'hymeis kata tēn sarka krinete egō ou krinō oudena',
   '''Ye judge after the flesh'' (kata tēn sarka krinete — you judge according to the flesh, by human/external standards). ''I judge no man'' — not a denial of his judicial authority (5:22, 27) but a statement that he does not judge in the manner they do: by appearances, by prejudice, by fleshly criteria. His judgment, when exercised, is true (v.16).',
   NULL),
  (16, 'And yet if I judge, my judgment is true: for I am not alone, but I and the Father that sent me.',
   'καὶ ἐὰν κρίνω δὲ ἐγώ ἡ κρίσις ἡ ἐμὴ ἀληθής ἐστιν ὅτι μόνος οὐκ εἰμί ἀλλ᾽ ἐγὼ καὶ ὁ πέμψας με πατήρ',
   'kai ean krinō de egō hē krisis hē emē alēthēs estin hoti monos ouk eimi all egō kai ho pempsas me patēr',
   '''I am not alone, but I and the Father'' — Jesus'' judgment is reliable because it is never solitary: the Father and Son judge together. This satisfies the ''two witnesses'' requirement (v.17-18) at the deepest level: the two witnesses are the Father and the Son.',
   NULL),
  (17, 'It is also written in your law, that the testimony of two men is true.',
   'καὶ ἐν τῷ νόμῳ δὲ τῷ ὑμετέρῳ γέγραπται ὅτι δύο ἀνθρώπων ἡ μαρτυρία ἀληθής ἐστιν',
   'kai en tō nomō de tō hymeterō gegraptai hoti duo anthrōpōn hē martyria alēthēs estin',
   '''Your law'' (tō hymeterō nomō — your law; not distancing himself from the law but emphasising their own legal standard). The reference is to Deuteronomy 17:6; 19:15 — two or three witnesses required. Jesus will provide the two witnesses in v.18.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'I am one that bear witness of myself, and the Father that sent me beareth witness of me.',
   'ἐγώ εἰμι ὁ μαρτυρῶν περὶ ἐμαυτοῦ καὶ μαρτυρεῖ περὶ ἐμοῦ ὁ πέμψας με πατήρ',
   'egō eimi ho martyrōn peri emautou kai martyrei peri emou ho pempsas me patēr',
   'Two witnesses: (1) Jesus himself (egō eimi ho martyrōn — I AM the one witnessing). (2) The Father who sent him (ho pempsas me patēr — the Father who sent me). Note that ''I am'' (egō eimi) opens the statement — in context, this may carry divine name overtones. The Father''s testimony comes through Jesus'' works (5:36), the Scriptures (5:39), and the inner witness of the Spirit.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'Then said they unto him, Where is thy Father? Jesus answered, Ye neither know me, nor my Father: if ye had known me, ye should have known my Father also.',
   'ἔλεγον οὖν αὐτῷ Ποῦ ἐστιν ὁ πατήρ σου ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς Οὔτε ἐμὲ οἴδατε οὔτε τὸν πατέρα μου εἰ ἐμὲ ᾔδειτε καὶ τὸν πατέρα μου ἂν ᾔδειτε',
   'elegon oun autō Pou estin ho patēr sou apekrithē Iēsous Oute eme oidate oute ton patera mou ei eme ēdeite kai ton patera mou an ēdeite',
   '''Where is thy Father?'' — they may mean it sarcastically (a slur on his birth) or literally (produce this witness). ''Ye neither know me, nor my Father'' — devastating: they are the religious experts, yet they know neither the Son nor the Father. ''If ye had known me, ye should have known my Father also'' — knowledge of the Father comes exclusively through the Son (cf. 14:7, 9: ''He that hath seen me hath seen the Father''). To reject the Son is to forfeit knowledge of the Father.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'These words spake Jesus in the treasury, as he taught in the temple: and no man laid hands on him; for his hour was not yet come.',
   'ταῦτα τὰ ῥήματα ἐλάλησεν ὁ Ἰησοῦς ἐν τῷ γαζοφυλακίῳ διδάσκων ἐν τῷ ἱερῷ καὶ οὐδεὶς ἐπίασεν αὐτόν ὅτι οὔπω ἐληλύθει ἡ ὥρα αὐτοῦ',
   'tauta ta rhēmata elalēsen ho Iēsous en tō gazophylakiō didaskōn en tō hierō kai oudeis epiasen auton hoti oupō elēlythei hē hōra autou',
   '''In the treasury'' (en tō gazophylakiō — in the area of the treasury, in the Court of Women where the offering boxes were and where the great candelabra of Tabernacles were lit). Jesus makes his ''Light of the world'' claim in the very place where the festival lights burned. ''No man laid hands on him; for his hour was not yet come'' — the refrain of divine sovereignty (cf. 7:30).',
   NULL),
  (21, 'Then said Jesus again unto them, I go my way, and ye shall seek me, and shall die in your sins: whither I go, ye cannot come.',
   'εἶπεν οὖν πάλιν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἐγὼ ὑπάγω καὶ ζητήσετέ με καὶ ἐν τῇ ἁμαρτίᾳ ὑμῶν ἀποθανεῖσθε ὅπου ἐγὼ ὑπάγω ὑμεῖς οὐ δύνασθε ἐλθεῖν',
   'eipen oun palin autois ho Iēsous Egō hypagō kai zētēsete me kai en tē hamartia hymōn apothaneisthe hopou egō hypagō hymeis ou dynasthe elthein',
   '''Ye shall die in your sins'' (en tē hamartia hymōn apothaneisthe — in your sin you will die). This is more severe than 7:34 (which omitted ''in your sins''). To die in one''s sins means to face death with guilt unremoved, unpardoned. ''Whither I go, ye cannot come'' — Jesus goes to the Father; those who reject him cannot follow. The warning is urgent: the opportunity to believe will not last forever.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'Then said the Jews, Will he kill himself? because he saith, Whither I go, ye cannot come.',
   'ἔλεγον οὖν οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι Μήτι ἀποκτενεῖ ἑαυτόν ὅτι λέγει Ὅπου ἐγὼ ὑπάγω ὑμεῖς οὐ δύνασθε ἐλθεῖν',
   'elegon oun hoi Ioudaioi Mēti apoktenei heauton hoti legei Hopou egō hypagō hymeis ou dynasthe elthein',
   '''Will he kill himself?'' — in 7:35 they wondered if he would go to the Diaspora; here they suggest suicide. Jewish tradition placed suicides in the lowest part of Hades — so ''where I go ye cannot come'' would mean Jesus goes to hell. The irony: Jesus will indeed lay down his life voluntarily (10:17-18), but this is not suicide — it is sacrifice.',
   NULL),
  (23, 'And he said unto them, Ye are from beneath; I am from above: ye are of this world; I am not of this world.',
   'καὶ εἶπεν αὐτοῖς Ὑμεῖς ἐκ τῶν κάτω ἐστέ ἐγὼ ἐκ τῶν ἄνω εἰμί ὑμεῖς ἐκ τοῦ κόσμου τούτου ἐστέ ἐγὼ οὐκ εἰμὶ ἐκ τοῦ κόσμου τούτου',
   'kai eipen autois Hymeis ek tōn katō este egō ek tōn anō eimi hymeis ek tou kosmou toutou este egō ouk eimi ek tou kosmou toutou',
   '''Ye are from beneath; I am from above'' (hymeis ek tōn katō — you are from the things below; egō ek tōn anō — I am from the things above). ''Ye are of this world; I am not of this world.'' The contrast is absolute: their origin is earthly, his is heavenly. ''This world'' (tou kosmou toutou) in John means the fallen world-system in rebellion against God (cf. 1:10; 15:18-19; 17:14-16). Jesus entered this world (1:14) but does not belong to it.',
   NULL),
  (24, 'I said therefore unto you, that ye shall die in your sins: for if ye believe not that I am he, ye shall die in your sins.',
   'εἶπον οὖν ὑμῖν ὅτι ἀποθανεῖσθε ἐν ταῖς ἁμαρτίαις ὑμῶν ἐὰν γὰρ μὴ πιστεύσητε ὅτι ἐγώ εἰμι ἀποθανεῖσθε ἐν ταῖς ἁμαρτίαις ὑμῶν',
   'eipon oun hymin hoti apothaneisthe en tais hamartiais hymōn ean gar mē pisteusēte hoti egō eimi apothaneisthe en tais hamartiais hymōn',
   '''If ye believe not that I am'' (ean mē pisteusēte hoti egō eimi — unless you believe that I AM). Note: ''he'' is italicised in the KJV because it is not in the Greek — the text reads simply egō eimi (I AM), the absolute divine self-designation. Believing that Jesus is the I AM — God incarnate — is the condition for escaping death in sin. Without faith in the deity of Christ, there is no salvation.',
   'This verse makes belief in Jesus'' divine identity the dividing line between salvation and damnation. ''If ye believe not that I AM'' — the absolute egō eimi without predicate. This is not merely ''I am the Messiah'' but ''I AM'' — the divine name (Exodus 3:14). The consequence of unbelief is dying ''in your sins'' (en tais hamartiais hymōn — plural, emphasising the accumulated weight of unforgiven sin). There is no alternative path to forgiveness: either one believes in the I AM and is freed from sin, or one rejects him and dies under sin''s condemnation.'),
  (25, 'Then said they unto him, Who art thou? And Jesus saith unto them, Even the same that I said unto you from the beginning.',
   'ἔλεγον οὖν αὐτῷ Σὺ τίς εἶ εἶπεν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Τὴν ἀρχὴν ὅ τι καὶ λαλῶ ὑμῖν',
   'elegon oun autō Sy tis ei eipen autois ho Iēsous Tēn archēn ho ti kai lalō hymin',
   '''Who art thou?'' (sy tis ei — who are you?). Jesus'' answer is notoriously difficult to translate. ''Even the same that I said unto you from the beginning'' is one rendering. Other translations: ''Why do I speak to you at all?'' or ''Exactly what I have been telling you from the start.'' The ambiguity may be intentional: Jesus has been declaring his identity throughout, and they still ask. His identity has been stated clearly — their problem is not lack of information but lack of faith.',
   NULL),
  (26, 'I have many things to say and to judge of you: but he that sent me is true; and I speak to the world those things which I have heard of him.',
   'πολλὰ ἔχω περὶ ὑμῶν λαλεῖν καὶ κρίνειν ἀλλ᾽ ὁ πέμψας με ἀληθής ἐστιν κἀγὼ ἃ ἤκουσα παρ᾽ αὐτοῦ ταῦτα λέγω εἰς τὸν κόσμον',
   'polla echō peri hymōn lalein kai krinein all ho pempsas me alēthēs estin kagō ha ēkousa par autou tauta legō eis ton kosmon',
   '''I have many things to say and to judge'' — Jesus restrains himself; he could say much more in judgment. ''He that sent me is true'' — the Father''s truthfulness guarantees the Son''s message. ''I speak to the world those things which I have heard of him'' — Jesus'' words originate in the Father''s communication to the Son.',
   NULL),
  (27, 'They understood not that he spake to them of the Father.',
   'οὐκ ἔγνωσαν ὅτι τὸν πατέρα αὐτοῖς ἔλεγεν',
   'ouk egnōsan hoti ton patera autois elegen',
   'They did not understand that ''he that sent me'' referred to the Father. Their spiritual blindness is remarkable — Jesus has spoken of the Father repeatedly, yet they cannot perceive it. This incomprehension underscores the spiritual darkness Jesus came to illuminate.',
   NULL),
  (28, 'Then said Jesus unto them, When ye have lifted up the Son of man, then shall ye know that I am he, and that I do nothing of myself; but as my Father hath taught me, I speak these things.',
   'εἶπεν οὖν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ὅταν ὑψώσητε τὸν υἱὸν τοῦ ἀνθρώπου τότε γνώσεσθε ὅτι ἐγώ εἰμι καὶ ἀπ᾽ ἐμαυτοῦ ποιῶ οὐδέν ἀλλὰ καθὼς ἐδίδαξέν με ὁ πατήρ ταῦτα λαλῶ',
   'eipen oun autois ho Iēsous Hotan hypsōsēte ton huion tou anthrōpou tote gnōsesthe hoti egō eimi kai ap emautou poiō ouden alla kathōs edidaxen me ho patēr tauta lalō',
   '''When ye have lifted up the Son of man'' (hotan hypsōsēte ton huion tou anthrōpou — when you lift up/exalt the Son of man). ''Lifted up'' (hypsōsēte — from hypsoō: to lift up, to exalt) has a double meaning in John: physically lifting on the cross and spiritually exalting in glory (cf. 3:14; 12:32-34). ''Then shall ye know that I am'' (tote gnōsesthe hoti egō eimi — then you will come to know that I AM). The cross will reveal Jesus'' identity: the centurion''s confession (Mark 15:39), the darkened sky, the torn veil, the resurrection — all confirm the I AM claim.',
   NULL),
  (29, 'And he that sent me is with me: the Father hath not left me alone; for I do always those things that please him.',
   'καὶ ὁ πέμψας με μετ᾽ ἐμοῦ ἐστιν οὐκ ἀφῆκέν με μόνον ὁ πατήρ ὅτι ἐγὼ τὰ ἀρεστὰ αὐτῷ ποιῶ πάντοτε',
   'kai ho pempsas me met emou estin ouk aphēken me monon ho patēr hoti egō ta aresta autō poiō pantote',
   '''The Father hath not left me alone'' — in contrast to the woman whose accusers left (v.9), the Father never leaves the Son. ''I do always those things that please him'' (ta aresta autō poiō pantote — the things pleasing to him I do always). This is an extraordinary claim to sinless, unbroken obedience — always, without exception, pleasing the Father. No mere human could truthfully say this.',
   NULL),
  (30, 'As he spake these words, many believed on him.',
   'ταῦτα αὐτοῦ λαλοῦντος πολλοὶ ἐπίστευσαν εἰς αὐτόν',
   'tauta autou lalountos polloi episteusan eis auton',
   '''Many believed on him'' (polloi episteusan eis auton). This sets the stage for vv.31-59, where Jesus addresses ''those Jews which believed on him'' (v.31). However, as the discourse progresses, these ''believers'' turn hostile (vv.48, 59), suggesting their initial belief was superficial — a pattern John has shown before (2:23-25; 6:60-66).',
   NULL),
  (31, 'Then said Jesus to those Jews which believed on him, If ye continue in my word, then are ye my disciples indeed;',
   'ἔλεγεν οὖν ὁ Ἰησοῦς πρὸς τοὺς πεπιστευκότας αὐτῷ Ἰουδαίους Ἐὰν ὑμεῖς μείνητε ἐν τῷ λόγῳ τῷ ἐμῷ ἀληθῶς μαθηταί μού ἐστε',
   'elegen oun ho Iēsous pros tous pepisteukotus autō Ioudaious Ean hymeis meinēte en tō logō tō emō alēthōs mathētai mou este',
   '''If ye continue in my word'' (ean hymeis meinēte en tō logō tō emō — if you remain/abide in my word). ''Then are ye my disciples indeed'' (alēthōs mathētai mou este — you are truly my disciples). True discipleship is not initial belief but continuing abidence. The test of genuine faith is perseverance — remaining in Christ''s word over time. Those who depart prove their faith was never real (cf. 1 John 2:19).',
   NULL),
  (32, 'And ye shall know the truth, and the truth shall make you free.',
   'καὶ γνώσεσθε τὴν ἀλήθειαν καὶ ἡ ἀλήθεια ἐλευθερώσει ὑμᾶς',
   'kai gnōsesthe tēn alētheian kai hē alētheia eleutherōsei hymas',
   '''Ye shall know the truth'' (gnōsesthe tēn alētheian — you will come to know the truth; future: a progressive, experiential knowledge that comes through continuing in his word). ''The truth shall make you free'' (hē alētheia eleutherōsei hymas — the truth will set you free). The ''truth'' is not abstract philosophical truth but Jesus himself (14:6: ''I am the truth'') and his word (17:17: ''Thy word is truth''). The freedom is from sin (v.34), death (v.51), and the devil (v.44) — not political freedom, as they misunderstand in v.33.',
   'This is one of the most quoted verses in Scripture, often lifted from context. The freedom Jesus offers is specifically spiritual: freedom from the bondage of sin (v.34: ''Whosoever committeth sin is the servant of sin''). The sequence is: (1) continue in the word → (2) become true disciples → (3) know the truth → (4) experience freedom. Knowledge that liberates is not mere information but personal, experiential acquaintance with Jesus, who is the Truth (14:6). This freedom is real freedom (v.36: ''free indeed''), unlike all human freedom which is constrained by sin.'),
  (33, 'They answered him, We be Abraham''s seed, and were never in bondage to any man: how sayest thou, Ye shall be made free?',
   'ἀπεκρίθησαν αὐτῷ Σπέρμα Ἀβραάμ ἐσμεν καὶ οὐδενὶ δεδουλεύκαμεν πώποτε πῶς σὺ λέγεις ὅτι Ἐλεύθεροι γενήσεσθε',
   'apekrithēsan autō Sperma Abraam esmen kai oudeni dedouleukamen pōpote pōs sy legeis hoti Eleutheroi genēsesthe',
   '''We be Abraham''s seed and were never in bondage'' — historically absurd: Egypt (400 years), Babylon (70 years), Persia, Greece, and now Rome. They are currently under Roman occupation. Their claim reveals self-deception on multiple levels: politically they deny their subjugation; spiritually they deny their bondage to sin. Abraham''s lineage provides ethnic identity but not spiritual freedom.',
   NULL),
  (34, 'Jesus answered them, Verily, verily, I say unto you, Whosoever committeth sin is the servant of sin.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν ὅτι πᾶς ὁ ποιῶν τὴν ἁμαρτίαν δοῦλός ἐστιν τῆς ἁμαρτίας',
   'apekrithē autois ho Iēsous Amēn amēn legō hymin hoti pas ho poiōn tēn hamartian doulos estin tēs hamartias',
   '''Whosoever committeth sin is the servant of sin'' (pas ho poiōn tēn hamartian doulos estin tēs hamartias — everyone who practices sin is a slave of sin). ''Committeth'' (ho poiōn — present participle: the one who keeps doing, practices habitually). Sin is not just an act but a master. The person who sins is not free but enslaved — addiction, compulsion, inability to stop. This slavery is universal: ''all have sinned'' (Romans 3:23). Only the Son can set free (v.36).',
   NULL),
  (35, 'And the servant abideth not in the house for ever: but the Son abideth ever.',
   'ὁ δὲ δοῦλος οὐ μένει ἐν τῇ οἰκίᾳ εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα ὁ υἱὸς μένει εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα',
   'ho de doulos ou menei en tē oikia eis ton aiōna ho huios menei eis ton aiōna',
   '''The servant abideth not... but the Son abideth ever.'' A slave has no permanent place in the household — he can be sold or expelled. The Son belongs permanently. Those enslaved to sin have no secure standing before God; the Son has eternal standing. The contrast sets up v.36: the Son''s permanent status enables him to grant permanent freedom to slaves.',
   NULL),
  (36, 'If the Son therefore shall make you free, ye shall be free indeed.',
   'ἐὰν οὖν ὁ υἱὸς ὑμᾶς ἐλευθερώσῃ ὄντως ἐλεύθεροι ἔσεσθε',
   'ean oun ho huios hymas eleutherōsē ontōs eleutheroi esesthe',
   '''If the Son... shall make you free'' (ean ho huios hymas eleutherōsē — if the Son sets you free). ''Free indeed'' (ontōs eleutheroi — truly, really free). Not the partial freedom of political liberation or philosophical enlightenment but real, ontological freedom — freedom from sin''s power, guilt, and penalty. Only the Son can do this because only the Son has authority over sin and death. The word ''indeed'' (ontōs — in reality, genuinely) contrasts with all false freedoms.',
   NULL),
  (37, 'I know that ye are Abraham''s seed; but ye seek to kill me, because my word hath no place in you.',
   'οἶδα ὅτι σπέρμα Ἀβραάμ ἐστε ἀλλὰ ζητεῖτέ με ἀποκτεῖναι ὅτι ὁ λόγος ὁ ἐμὸς οὐ χωρεῖ ἐν ὑμῖν',
   'oida hoti sperma Abraam este alla zēteite me apokteinai hoti ho logos ho emos ou chōrei en hymin',
   '''I know that ye are Abraham''s seed'' — Jesus concedes their physical descent from Abraham. ''But ye seek to kill me'' — their actions contradict their heritage. ''My word hath no place in you'' (ho logos ho emos ou chōrei en hymin — my word does not advance/find room in you). Chōreō means to make room, to progress — Jesus'' word cannot penetrate their hearts. They are physically Abraham''s children but spiritually they prove to have a different father (v.44).',
   NULL),
  (38, 'I speak that which I have seen with my Father: and ye do that which ye have seen with your father.',
   'ἐγὼ ὃ ἑώρακα παρὰ τῷ πατρί μου λαλῶ καὶ ὑμεῖς οὖν ὃ ἑωράκατε παρὰ τῷ πατρὶ ὑμῶν ποιεῖτε',
   'egō ho heōraka para tō patri mou lalō kai hymeis oun ho heōrakate para tō patri hymōn poieite',
   'Two fathers, two behaviours: Jesus speaks what he has seen with his Father (God); they do what they have seen with their father (whom Jesus will identify as the devil in v.44). Children imitate their parents. Behaviour reveals parentage — not biology but spiritual allegiance.',
   NULL),
  (39, 'They answered and said unto him, Abraham is our father. Jesus saith unto them, If ye were Abraham''s children, ye would do the works of Abraham.',
   'ἀπεκρίθησαν καὶ εἶπον αὐτῷ Ὁ πατὴρ ἡμῶν Ἀβραάμ ἐστιν λέγει αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Εἰ τέκνα τοῦ Ἀβραὰμ ἦτε τὰ ἔργα τοῦ Ἀβραὰμ ἐποιεῖτε ἂν',
   'apekrithēsan kai eipon autō Ho patēr hēmōn Abraam estin legei autois ho Iēsous Ei tekna tou Abraam ēte ta erga tou Abraam epoieite an',
   '''If ye were Abraham''s children'' — Jesus shifts from ''seed'' (sperma, physical descent, v.37) to ''children'' (tekna, spiritual character). Abraham''s true children share Abraham''s faith and works. Abraham believed God (Genesis 15:6); they disbelieve. Abraham welcomed divine messengers (Genesis 18:1-8); they seek to kill the divine messenger.',
   NULL),
  (40, 'But now ye seek to kill me, a man that hath told you the truth, which I have heard of God: this did not Abraham.',
   'νῦν δὲ ζητεῖτέ με ἀποκτεῖναι ἄνθρωπον ὃς τὴν ἀλήθειαν ὑμῖν λελάληκα ἣν ἤκουσα παρὰ τοῦ θεοῦ τοῦτο Ἀβραὰμ οὐκ ἐποίησεν',
   'nyn de zēteite me apokteinai anthrōpon hos tēn alētheian hymin lelalēka hēn ēkousa para tou theou touto Abraam ouk epoiēsen',
   '''A man that hath told you the truth'' — Jesus describes himself as one who speaks truth heard from God. ''This did not Abraham'' (touto Abraam ouk epoiēsen — Abraham did not do this). Abraham did not attempt to murder God''s messenger; he received God''s word with faith (Genesis 15:6). Their murderous intent proves they are not Abraham''s spiritual children.',
   NULL),
  (41, 'Ye do the deeds of your father. Then said they to him, We be not born of fornication; we have one Father, even God.',
   'ὑμεῖς ποιεῖτε τὰ ἔργα τοῦ πατρὸς ὑμῶν εἶπον οὖν αὐτῷ Ἡμεῖς ἐκ πορνείας οὐ γεγεννήμεθα ἕνα πατέρα ἔχομεν τὸν θεόν',
   'hymeis poieite ta erga tou patros hymōn eipon oun autō Hēmeis ek porneias ou gegennēmetha hena patera echomen ton theon',
   '''We be not born of fornication'' (hēmeis ek porneias ou gegennēmetha — we were not born of sexual immorality). This may be: (1) a slur against Jesus'' birth (implying illegitimacy), or (2) a claim that they are not spiritual idolaters (the OT uses ''fornication'' as a metaphor for idolatry, Hosea 1:2; 2:4). ''We have one Father, even God'' — they escalate from Abraham to God himself. Jesus will demolish this claim in vv.42-44.',
   NULL),
  (42, 'Jesus said unto them, If God were your Father, ye would love me: for I proceeded forth and came from God; neither came I of myself, but he sent me.',
   'εἶπεν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Εἰ ὁ θεὸς πατὴρ ὑμῶν ἦν ἠγαπᾶτε ἂν ἐμέ ἐγὼ γὰρ ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ ἐξῆλθον καὶ ἥκω οὐδὲ γὰρ ἀπ᾽ ἐμαυτοῦ ἐλήλυθα ἀλλ᾽ ἐκεῖνός με ἀπέστειλεν',
   'eipen autois ho Iēsous Ei ho theos patēr hymōn ēn ēgapate an eme egō gar ek tou theou exēlthon kai hēkō oude gar ap emautou elēlytha all ekeinos me apesteilen',
   '''If God were your Father, ye would love me'' — the test is simple: do you love Jesus? If God is truly your Father, you will love the Son he sent. Their hatred of Jesus proves God is not their Father. ''I proceeded forth and came from God'' (ek tou theou exēlthon kai hēkō — I came out from God and have arrived). Two verbs: exēlthon (went out, denoting origin) and hēkō (have come, denoting present arrival). Jesus'' origin is divine, his mission is divinely commissioned.',
   NULL),
  (43, 'Why do ye not understand my speech? even because ye cannot hear my word.',
   'διατί τὴν λαλιὰν τὴν ἐμὴν οὐ γινώσκετε ὅτι οὐ δύνασθε ἀκούειν τὸν λόγον τὸν ἐμόν',
   'diati tēn lalian tēn emēn ou ginōskete hoti ou dynasthe akouein ton logon ton emon',
   '''Why do ye not understand my speech?'' (diati tēn lalian tēn emēn ou ginōskete — why do you not recognise my mode of speaking?). ''Because ye cannot hear my word'' (hoti ou dynasthe akouein ton logon ton emon — because you are not able to hear my word). Jesus distinguishes between lalian (speech, manner of speaking) and logon (word, message, content). They cannot understand his speech because they cannot receive his message. The inability is moral, not intellectual — their hearts are closed to divine truth.',
   NULL),
  (44, 'Ye are of your father the devil, and the lusts of your father ye will do. He was a murderer from the beginning, and abode not in the truth, because there is no truth in him. When he speaketh a lie, he speaketh of his own: for he is a liar, and the father of it.',
   'ὑμεῖς ἐκ τοῦ πατρὸς τοῦ διαβόλου ἐστὲ καὶ τὰς ἐπιθυμίας τοῦ πατρὸς ὑμῶν θέλετε ποιεῖν ἐκεῖνος ἀνθρωποκτόνος ἦν ἀπ᾽ ἀρχῆς καὶ ἐν τῇ ἀληθείᾳ οὐχ ἕστηκεν ὅτι οὐκ ἔστιν ἀλήθεια ἐν αὐτῷ ὅταν λαλῇ τὸ ψεῦδος ἐκ τῶν ἰδίων λαλεῖ ὅτι ψεύστης ἐστὶν καὶ ὁ πατὴρ αὐτοῦ',
   'hymeis ek tou patros tou diabolou este kai tas epithymias tou patros hymōn thelete poiein ekeinos anthrōpoktonos ēn ap archēs kai en tē alētheia ouch hestēken hoti ouk estin alētheia en autō hotan lalē to pseudos ek tōn idiōn lalei hoti pseustēs estin kai ho patēr autou',
   '''Ye are of your father the devil'' (hymeis ek tou patros tou diabolou este — you are from the father, the devil). ''The lusts of your father ye will do'' (tas epithymias tou patros hymōn thelete poiein — the desires of your father you wish to carry out). ''He was a murderer from the beginning'' (anthrōpoktonos ēn ap archēs — a man-killer from the beginning; referring to Satan''s role in the fall, which brought death to humanity, Genesis 3; and possibly to Cain, 1 John 3:12). ''There is no truth in him'' — truth and the devil are fundamentally incompatible. ''He is a liar, and the father of it'' (pseustēs estin kai ho patēr autou — he is a liar and the father of lies). Two characteristics of the devil: murder and lies. Those who seek to murder Jesus and reject his truth prove their spiritual paternity.',
   'This is the most explicit statement of satanic paternity in Scripture. Jesus does not accuse them of being demon-possessed but of belonging to Satan''s family — sharing his character (lies) and his agenda (murder). The identification is based on behaviour: children resemble their father. Since the devil is characterised by murder and lies, those who seek to kill Jesus (murder) and reject his truth (lies) demonstrate that they are the devil''s children, not God''s. This does not mean they are beyond redemption — Paul, who once persecuted the church, was transformed by grace. But without repentance and faith, they remain in the devil''s family.'),
  (45, 'And because I tell you the truth, ye believe me not.',
   'ἐγὼ δὲ ὅτι τὴν ἀλήθειαν λέγω οὐ πιστεύετέ μοι',
   'egō de hoti tēn alētheian legō ou pisteuete moi',
   'The paradox of unbelief: they do not believe because Jesus tells the truth. If he told them comfortable lies, they would believe. Truth offends because it exposes — and those who love darkness hate exposure (3:20). The more truthful the message, the more hostile the reception from those committed to falsehood.',
   NULL),
  (46, 'Which of you convinceth me of sin? And if I say the truth, why do ye not believe me?',
   'τίς ἐξ ὑμῶν ἐλέγχει με περὶ ἁμαρτίας εἰ δὲ ἀλήθειαν λέγω διατί ὑμεῖς οὐ πιστεύετέ μοι',
   'tis ex hymōn elenchei me peri hamartias ei de alētheian legō diati hymeis ou pisteuete moi',
   '''Which of you convinceth me of sin?'' (tis ex hymōn elenchei me peri hamartias — who among you convicts me of sin?). An extraordinary challenge: Jesus invites his enemies to identify a single sin in him. No one responds. This is not arrogance but a unique claim to sinlessness — confirmed by the NT witness (2 Corinthians 5:21; Hebrews 4:15; 1 Peter 2:22; 1 John 3:5). If he is sinless, his testimony is trustworthy. If he speaks truth, why not believe?',
   NULL),
  (47, 'He that is of God heareth God''s words: ye therefore hear them not, because ye are not of God.',
   'ὁ ὢν ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ τὰ ῥήματα τοῦ θεοῦ ἀκούει διὰ τοῦτο ὑμεῖς οὐκ ἀκούετε ὅτι ἐκ τοῦ θεοῦ οὐκ ἐστέ',
   'ho ōn ek tou theou ta rhēmata tou theou akouei dia touto hymeis ouk akouete hoti ek tou theou ouk este',
   '''He that is of God heareth God''s words'' — the principle from 10:27 (''My sheep hear my voice''). ''Ye hear them not, because ye are not of God'' — their inability to hear is diagnostic: it reveals their spiritual origin. Being ''of God'' (ek tou theou) means being born of God, belonging to God. Those who belong to God recognise God''s voice in Jesus; those who do not belong cannot hear.',
   NULL),
  (48, 'Then answered the Jews, and said unto him, Say we not well that thou art a Samaritan, and hast a devil?',
   'ἀπεκρίθησαν οὖν οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι καὶ εἶπον αὐτῷ Οὐ καλῶς λέγομεν ἡμεῖς ὅτι Σαμαρείτης εἶ σὺ καὶ δαιμόνιον ἔχεις',
   'apekrithēsan oun hoi Ioudaioi kai eipon autō Ou kalōs legomen hēmeis hoti Samareitēs ei sy kai daimonion echeis',
   '''A Samaritan'' — the worst ethnic insult: Samaritans were despised as half-breeds and heretics. ''Hast a devil'' (daimonion echeis — you have a demon; cf. 7:20; 10:20). Unable to refute his arguments, they resort to personal attacks. This is the pattern of defeated debate: when you cannot answer the argument, attack the person.',
   NULL),
  (49, 'Jesus answered, I have not a devil; but I honour my Father, and ye do dishonour me.',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς Ἐγὼ δαιμόνιον οὐκ ἔχω ἀλλὰ τιμῶ τὸν πατέρα μου καὶ ὑμεῖς ἀτιμάζετέ με',
   'apekrithē Iēsous Egō daimonion ouk echō alla timō ton patera mou kai hymeis atimazete me',
   'Jesus ignores the ''Samaritan'' slur and addresses only the demon charge: ''I have not a devil.'' He contrasts his purpose (honouring the Father) with their action (dishonouring him). To dishonour the Son is to dishonour the Father (5:23).',
   NULL),
  (50, 'And I seek not mine own glory: there is one that seeketh and judgeth.',
   'ἐγὼ δὲ οὐ ζητῶ τὴν δόξαν μου ἔστιν ὁ ζητῶν καὶ κρίνων',
   'egō de ou zētō tēn doxan mou estin ho zētōn kai krinōn',
   '''I seek not mine own glory'' — echoing 5:41 and 7:18. ''There is one that seeketh and judgeth'' — the Father seeks the Son''s glory and judges those who dishonour him. Jesus does not need to defend his own honour; the Father will vindicate him.',
   NULL),
  (51, 'Verily, verily, I say unto you, If a man keep my saying, he shall never see death.',
   'ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν ἐάν τις τὸν ἐμὸν λόγον τηρήσῃ θάνατον οὐ μὴ θεωρήσῃ εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα',
   'amēn amēn legō hymin ean tis ton emon logon tērēsē thanaton ou mē theōrēsē eis ton aiōna',
   '''If a man keep my saying'' (ean tis ton emon logon tērēsē — if anyone guards/keeps my word). ''He shall never see death'' (thanaton ou mē theōrēsē eis ton aiōna — he will absolutely never see death, ever). ''See'' (theōrēsē — contemplate, experience). Jesus does not promise immunity from physical death but freedom from the ultimate reality of death — eternal separation from God. The believer experiences physical death as a passage, not a terminus (cf. 11:25-26).',
   NULL),
  (52, 'Then said the Jews unto him, Now we know that thou hast a devil. Abraham is dead, and the prophets; and thou sayest, If a man keep my saying, he shall never taste of death.',
   'εἶπον οὖν αὐτῷ οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι Νῦν ἐγνώκαμεν ὅτι δαιμόνιον ἔχεις Ἀβραὰμ ἀπέθανεν καὶ οἱ προφῆται καὶ σὺ λέγεις Ἐάν τις τὸν λόγον μου τηρήσῃ οὐ μὴ γεύσηται θανάτου εἰς τὸν αἰῶνα',
   'eipon oun autō hoi Ioudaioi Nyn egnōkamen hoti daimonion echeis Abraam apethanen kai hoi prophētai kai sy legeis Ean tis ton logon mou tērēsē ou mē geusētai thanatou eis ton aiōna',
   '''Abraham is dead, and the prophets'' — their objection: Abraham and the prophets kept God''s word, yet they died. You claim your followers will never die — you must be mad. ''Never taste of death'' (ou mē geusētai thanatou — will never experience death). They take Jesus literally; he speaks spiritually. They look at Abraham''s grave; he looks at Abraham''s soul.',
   NULL),
  (53, 'Art thou greater than our father Abraham, which is dead? and the prophets are dead: whom makest thou thyself?',
   'μὴ σὺ μείζων εἶ τοῦ πατρὸς ἡμῶν Ἀβραὰμ ὅστις ἀπέθανεν καὶ οἱ προφῆται ἀπέθανον τίνα σεαυτὸν σὺ ποιεῖς',
   'mē sy meizōn ei tou patros hēmōn Abraam hostis apethanen kai hoi prophētai apethanon tina seauton sy poieis',
   '''Art thou greater than our father Abraham?'' (mē sy meizōn ei — surely you are not greater?). ''Whom makest thou thyself?'' (tina seauton sy poieis — who do you make yourself out to be?). The ironic question: the implied answer is ''no,'' but the true answer is ''infinitely greater.'' Jesus will answer this question definitively in v.58.',
   NULL),
  (54, 'Jesus answered, If I honour myself, my honour is nothing: it is my Father that honoureth me; of whom ye say, that he is your God:',
   'ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς Ἐὰν ἐγὼ δοξάζω ἐμαυτόν ἡ δόξα μου οὐδέν ἐστιν ἔστιν ὁ πατήρ μου ὁ δοξάζων με ὃν ὑμεῖς λέγετε ὅτι θεὸς ὑμῶν ἐστιν',
   'apekrithē Iēsous Ean egō doxazō emauton hē doxa mou ouden estin estin ho patēr mou ho doxazōn me hon hymeis legete hoti theos hymōn estin',
   '''If I honour myself, my honour is nothing'' — self-glorification is empty. ''It is my Father that honoureth me'' — Jesus'' glory comes from the Father. ''Of whom ye say, that he is your God'' — they claim God as their God, but if they truly knew God they would honour the one God honours. The disconnect is total: they claim God but reject God''s Son.',
   NULL),
  (55, 'Yet ye have not known him; but I know him: and if I should say, I know him not, I shall be a liar like unto you: but I know him, and keep his saying.',
   'καὶ οὐκ ἐγνώκατε αὐτόν ἐγὼ δὲ οἶδα αὐτόν κἂν εἴπω ὅτι οὐκ οἶδα αὐτόν ἔσομαι ὅμοιος ὑμῶν ψεύστης ἀλλ᾽ οἶδα αὐτὸν καὶ τὸν λόγον αὐτοῦ τηρῶ',
   'kai ouk egnōkate auton egō de oida auton kan eipō hoti ouk oida auton esomai homoios hymōn pseustēs all oida auton kai ton logon autou tērō',
   '''Ye have not known him'' (ouk egnōkate auton — you have not come to know him; perfect tense: you still do not know him). ''I know him'' (oida auton — I know him with settled, certain, immediate knowledge). ''If I should say, I know him not, I shall be a liar like unto you'' — the word ''like unto you'' (homoios hymōn) is devastating: you are liars. The only way for Jesus to fit into their paradigm would be for him to lie about knowing God — and he refuses.',
   NULL),
  (56, 'Your father Abraham rejoiced to see my day: and he saw it, and was glad.',
   'Ἀβραὰμ ὁ πατὴρ ὑμῶν ἠγαλλιάσατο ἵνα ἴδῃ τὴν ἡμέραν τὴν ἐμήν καὶ εἶδεν καὶ ἐχάρη',
   'Abraam ho patēr hymōn ēgalliasato hina idē tēn hēmeran tēn emēn kai eiden kai echarē',
   '''Abraham rejoiced to see my day'' (ēgalliasato hina idē tēn hēmeran tēn emēn — leaped for joy at the prospect of seeing my day). ''He saw it, and was glad'' (eiden kai echarē — he saw and rejoiced). When did Abraham see Jesus'' day? Possibilities: (1) The promise of the seed (Genesis 12:3; 22:18). (2) The birth of Isaac, the son of promise (Genesis 21:1-6; Hebrews 11:17-19). (3) A direct prophetic revelation. (4) From Paradise/heaven, Abraham sees the fulfilment. The point: Abraham, whom they claim as father, saw Jesus'' day and rejoiced. They see Jesus in person and want to kill him.',
   NULL),
  (57, 'Then said the Jews unto him, Thou art not yet fifty years old, and hast thou seen Abraham?',
   'εἶπον οὖν οἱ Ἰουδαῖοι πρὸς αὐτόν Πεντήκοντα ἔτη οὔπω ἔχεις καὶ Ἀβραὰμ ἑώρακας',
   'eipon oun hoi Ioudaioi pros auton Pentēkonta etē oupō echeis kai Abraam heōrakas',
   '''Not yet fifty years old'' (pentēkonta etē oupō echeis — you do not yet have fifty years). Jesus was about 33; they round up to an obviously implausible maximum. ''Hast thou seen Abraham?'' — they reverse Jesus'' statement: he said Abraham saw ''my day''; they ask if Jesus has seen Abraham. Both misunderstanding and scorn.',
   NULL),
  (58, 'Jesus said unto them, Verily, verily, I say unto you, Before Abraham was, I am.',
   'εἶπεν αὐτοῖς ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ἀμὴν ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν πρὶν Ἀβραὰμ γενέσθαι ἐγὼ εἰμί',
   'eipen autois ho Iēsous Amēn amēn legō hymin prin Abraam genesthai egō eimi',
   '''Before Abraham was'' (prin Abraam genesthai — before Abraham came into being; genesthai: aorist of ginomai — to come into existence, to be born). ''I am'' (egō eimi — I AM; present tense, not ''I was''). The contrast is deliberate: Abraham ''came into being'' (genesthai — a point in time) but Jesus ''I am'' (eimi — continuous, timeless existence). Jesus does not say ''Before Abraham was, I was'' (which would claim merely pre-existence) but ''I am'' (which claims eternal, timeless being — the divine name from Exodus 3:14). This is the supreme christological claim in the Gospel of John.',
   'This is the climactic ''I AM'' of John''s Gospel — the absolute, unqualified use of the divine name. The Jews understand perfectly: (1) Jesus claims to have existed before Abraham (c. 2000 BC). (2) He uses the present tense ''I am,'' claiming not just pre-existence but eternal, timeless self-existence. (3) He deliberately echoes the divine name (Exodus 3:14: ''I AM THAT I AM''). Their immediate response — picking up stones to kill him (v.59) — confirms they understood this as a claim to deity, which they considered blasphemy (Leviticus 24:16). If Jesus is not God, this is the most outrageous claim in human history. If he is God, it is the most important truth ever spoken.'),
  (59, 'Then took they up stones to cast at him: but Jesus hid himself, and went out of the temple, going through the midst of them, and so passed by.',
   'ἦραν οὖν λίθους ἵνα βάλωσιν ἐπ᾽ αὐτόν Ἰησοῦς δὲ ἐκρύβη καὶ ἐξῆλθεν ἐκ τοῦ ἱεροῦ διελθὼν διὰ μέσου αὐτῶν καὶ παρῆγεν οὕτως',
   'ēran oun lithous hina balōsin ep auton Iēsous de ekrybē kai exēlthen ek tou hierou dielthōn dia mesou autōn kai parēgen houtōs',
   '''Took they up stones'' (ēran lithous — they picked up stones). In the temple courts, construction materials for ongoing renovation of Herod''s temple were available. Stoning was the penalty for blasphemy (Leviticus 24:16). ''Jesus hid himself'' (Iēsous ekrybē — Jesus was hidden; the passive may suggest divine concealment). ''Going through the midst of them'' — a miraculous departure, as in Luke 4:30. His hour had not yet come (cf. 7:30; 8:20). He cannot be killed until the appointed time.',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 8;

-- Step 3: Insert word studies
INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, usage_notes, word_order)
SELECT v.id, ws.original_word, ws.transliteration, ws.strongs_number, ws.meaning, ws.usage_notes, ws.word_order
FROM (VALUES
  ('φῶς', 'phōs', 'G5457',
   'Light, radiance, luminance; the opposite of darkness; the revelation of God.',
   'In v.12, ''I am the light of the world'' (egō eimi to phōs tou kosmou). Phōs is foundational in John: ''In him was life; and the life was the light of men'' (1:4). ''The light shineth in darkness'' (1:5). ''That was the true Light, which lighteth every man'' (1:9). ''Men loved darkness rather than light'' (3:19). ''I am the light of the world'' (8:12; 9:5; 12:46). In the OT, God is light: ''The LORD is my light'' (Psalm 27:1); ''the LORD shall be unto thee an everlasting light'' (Isaiah 60:19). Jesus claims this divine attribute, fulfilling the Tabernacles lamplight ceremony.',
   1),
  ('ἀλήθεια', 'alētheia', 'G225',
   'Truth, reality, genuineness; that which corresponds to fact and reveals reality.',
   'Alētheia appears 8 times in John 8 (vv.32, 40, 44, 45, 46), more than any other chapter. In v.32, ''the truth shall make you free'' — truth is liberating. In v.40, Jesus speaks ''the truth which I have heard of God.'' In v.44, the devil ''abode not in the truth'' — truth and Satan are incompatible. In v.45, ''because I tell you the truth, ye believe me not'' — truth provokes hostility in those committed to lies. Jesus himself is the Truth (14:6). Truth in John is not abstract philosophy but the self-revelation of God in Christ.',
   2),
  ('ἐλεύθερος', 'eleutheros', 'G1658',
   'Free, at liberty, not a slave; one who possesses genuine freedom.',
   'In v.32, ''the truth shall make you free'' (eleutherōsei). In v.33, the Jews deny bondage. In v.36, ''if the Son shall make you free, ye shall be free indeed'' (ontōs eleutheroi). The freedom Jesus offers is from sin''s slavery (v.34), the devil''s family (v.44), and death''s power (v.51). It is not political or economic freedom but ontological — a fundamental change in one''s condition. Only the Son can grant this freedom because only the Son has authority over sin. Roman, Greek, and Enlightenment concepts of freedom are shadows of the reality Christ provides.',
   3),
  ('δοῦλος', 'doulos', 'G1401',
   'Slave, bondservant, one in bondage; one who belongs to and serves a master.',
   'In v.34, ''Whosoever committeth sin is the slave of sin'' (doulos estin tēs hamartias). Sin is not just an action but a master. The sinner is not free but enslaved — unable to stop sinning by willpower alone. This is the universal human condition: ''all have sinned'' (Romans 3:23) and all are enslaved. The slave has no permanent standing (v.35); only the Son can manumit (set free). Paul develops this: believers are freed from slavery to sin and become slaves of righteousness (Romans 6:17-18).',
   4),
  ('ψεύστης', 'pseustēs', 'G5583',
   'Liar, one who speaks falsehood; one whose character is defined by deception.',
   'In v.44, the devil ''is a liar and the father of it'' (pseustēs estin kai ho patēr autou). In v.55, Jesus says if he denied knowing the Father ''I shall be a liar like unto you'' (esomai homoios hymōn pseustēs). Truth and lies are not merely intellectual categories but moral and spiritual allegiances. Those who reject truth align with the Father of Lies; those who receive truth align with the God of Truth. 1 John 2:22: ''Who is a liar but he that denieth that Jesus is the Christ?''',
   5),
  ('ἁμαρτία', 'hamartia', 'G266',
   'Sin, missing the mark, moral failure; the fundamental human condition of alienation from God.',
   'Hamartia appears 4 times in John 8: v.21 (''ye shall die in your sin''), v.24 (''ye shall die in your sins''), v.34 (''whosoever committeth sin is the servant of sin''), v.46 (''which of you convinceth me of sin?''). Sin in John 8 is presented as: (1) a condition that leads to death (v.21, 24), (2) a master that enslaves (v.34), (3) something Jesus is uniquely free from (v.46). The singular ''sin'' (hamartia) in v.21 may refer to the root sin of unbelief — the sin that underlies all other sins.',
   6),
  ('ἐγώ εἰμι', 'egō eimi', 'G1473/G1510',
   'I AM — the absolute self-designation echoing the divine name of Exodus 3:14.',
   'The absolute egō eimi (without predicate) appears three times in John 8: v.24 (''if ye believe not that I am''), v.28 (''then shall ye know that I am''), and v.58 (''Before Abraham was, I am''). In v.12, it appears with a predicate (''I am the light of the world''). The absolute use is the most confrontational: it claims not merely a role (bread, light, shepherd) but identity — the divine ''I AM'' of Exodus 3:14. The progression builds: v.24 demands faith in the I AM; v.28 predicts knowledge after the cross; v.58 makes the ultimate claim of eternal pre-existence using the divine name.',
   7),
  ('ὑψόω', 'hypsoō', 'G5312',
   'To lift up, to elevate, to exalt; in John, the double meaning of crucifixion and glorification.',
   'In v.28, ''when ye have lifted up the Son of man'' (hotan hypsōsēte ton huion tou anthrōpou). Hypsoō in John carries a profound double meaning: physically, Jesus is ''lifted up'' on the cross; spiritually, he is ''exalted'' in glory. The two are inseparable: the cross is the throne. Cf. 3:14 (''as Moses lifted up the serpent... so must the Son of man be lifted up'') and 12:32 (''I, if I be lifted up from the earth, will draw all men unto me''). The crucifixion is not defeat but revelation — ''then shall ye know that I AM.''',
   8)
) AS ws(original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, usage_notes, word_order)
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
  SELECT v2.id FROM verses v2
  JOIN chapters c2 ON v2.chapter_id = c2.id
  JOIN books b2 ON c2.book_id = b2.id
  WHERE b2.name = 'John' AND c2.chapter_number = 8
  AND v2.verse_number = CASE ws.word_order
    WHEN 1 THEN 12
    WHEN 2 THEN 32
    WHEN 3 THEN 36
    WHEN 4 THEN 34
    WHEN 5 THEN 44
    WHEN 6 THEN 34
    WHEN 7 THEN 58
    WHEN 8 THEN 28
  END
) v;

-- Step 4: Insert cross-references
INSERT INTO cross_references (verse_id, reference, context, ref_order)
SELECT v.id, cr.referenced_verse, cr.note, ROW_NUMBER() OVER ()::int
FROM (VALUES
  -- v.7: Without sin cast the first stone
  (7, 'Deuteronomy 17:7', 'context', '''The hands of the witnesses shall be first upon him'' — the witnesses must throw the first stones'),
  (7, 'Romans 3:23', 'thematic', '''All have sinned, and come short of the glory of God'''),
  -- v.11: Go and sin no more
  (11, 'John 5:14', 'parallel', '''Sin no more, lest a worse thing come unto thee'' — the same command at Bethesda'),
  (11, 'Romans 8:1', 'thematic', '''There is therefore now no condemnation to them which are in Christ Jesus'''),
  -- v.12: I am the light of the world
  (12, 'Psalm 27:1', 'allusion', '''The LORD is my light and my salvation'' — Jesus claims the divine attribute of light'),
  (12, 'Isaiah 9:2', 'prophecy', '''The people that walked in darkness have seen a great light'''),
  (12, 'Isaiah 60:19-20', 'prophecy', '''The LORD shall be unto thee an everlasting light'' — Jesus fulfils this'),
  (12, 'John 1:4-5', 'thematic', '''In him was life; and the life was the light of men. And the light shineth in darkness'''),
  (12, 'John 9:5', 'parallel', '''As long as I am in the world, I am the light of the world'''),
  -- v.24: If ye believe not that I am
  (24, 'Exodus 3:14', 'allusion', '''I AM THAT I AM'' — the divine name Jesus claims'),
  (24, 'Mark 16:16', 'thematic', '''He that believeth not shall be damned'''),
  -- v.28: Lifted up the Son of man
  (28, 'John 3:14', 'parallel', '''As Moses lifted up the serpent... so must the Son of man be lifted up'''),
  (28, 'John 12:32-33', 'parallel', '''I, if I be lifted up from the earth, will draw all men unto me'''),
  (28, 'Isaiah 52:13', 'prophecy', '''My servant shall... be exalted and extolled, and be very high'' — lifted up in suffering and glory'),
  -- v.32: The truth shall make you free
  (32, 'John 14:6', 'thematic', '''I am the way, the truth, and the life'' — Jesus is the truth that liberates'),
  (32, 'John 17:17', 'thematic', '''Sanctify them through thy truth: thy word is truth'''),
  (32, 'Romans 6:18', 'thematic', '''Being then made free from sin, ye became the servants of righteousness'''),
  -- v.34: Servant of sin
  (34, 'Romans 6:16-20', 'thematic', '''His servants ye are to whom ye obey; whether of sin unto death, or of obedience unto righteousness'''),
  (34, '2 Peter 2:19', 'thematic', '''Of whom a man is overcome, of the same is he brought in bondage'''),
  -- v.36: Free indeed
  (36, 'Galatians 5:1', 'thematic', '''Stand fast therefore in the liberty wherewith Christ hath made us free'''),
  -- v.39: Abraham''s children do Abraham''s works
  (39, 'Romans 4:12', 'thematic', '''Walk in the steps of that faith of our father Abraham'''),
  (39, 'Galatians 3:7', 'thematic', '''They which are of faith, the same are the children of Abraham'''),
  -- v.44: Your father the devil
  (44, 'Genesis 3:4-5', 'allusion', 'The serpent''s lie in Eden — the devil as liar and murderer ''from the beginning'''),
  (44, '1 John 3:8', 'thematic', '''He that committeth sin is of the devil; for the devil sinneth from the beginning'''),
  (44, '1 John 3:12', 'thematic', '''Cain, who was of that wicked one, and slew his brother'' — murder from the devil'),
  -- v.46: Which of you convinceth me of sin?
  (46, '2 Corinthians 5:21', 'thematic', '''He hath made him to be sin for us, who knew no sin'''),
  (46, 'Hebrews 4:15', 'thematic', '''In all points tempted like as we are, yet without sin'''),
  (46, '1 Peter 2:22', 'thematic', '''Who did no sin, neither was guile found in his mouth'''),
  -- v.51: Never see death
  (51, 'John 11:25-26', 'thematic', '''He that believeth in me, though he were dead, yet shall he live'''),
  (51, 'John 5:24', 'parallel', '''He that heareth my word... hath everlasting life, and shall not come into condemnation'''),
  -- v.56: Abraham rejoiced to see my day
  (56, 'Genesis 12:1-3', 'allusion', 'The Abrahamic covenant — the promise of blessing through Abraham''s seed'),
  (56, 'Hebrews 11:13', 'thematic', '''These all died in faith... having seen them afar off, and were persuaded of them'''),
  -- v.58: Before Abraham was I am
  (58, 'Exodus 3:14', 'allusion', '''I AM THAT I AM'' — the burning bush revelation of the divine name'),
  (58, 'John 1:1', 'thematic', '''In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God'''),
  (58, 'John 17:5', 'thematic', '''The glory which I had with thee before the world was'''),
  (58, 'Colossians 1:17', 'thematic', '''He is before all things, and by him all things consist'''),
  (58, 'Revelation 1:8', 'thematic', '''I am Alpha and Omega... which is, and which was, and which is to come, the Almighty'''),
  -- v.59: Took up stones — blasphemy charge
  (59, 'Leviticus 24:16', 'context', '''He that blasphemeth the name of the LORD... shall surely be put to death... shall stone him'''),
  (59, 'John 10:31-33', 'parallel', '''The Jews took up stones again... for blasphemy; because that thou, being a man, makest thyself God''')
) AS cr(verse_number, referenced_verse, relationship_type, note)
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
  SELECT v2.id FROM verses v2
  JOIN chapters c2 ON v2.chapter_id = c2.id
  JOIN books b2 ON c2.book_id = b2.id
  WHERE b2.name = 'John' AND c2.chapter_number = 8 AND v2.verse_number = cr.verse_number
) v;

-- JOHN CHAPTER 8 — BACKFILL (additional word_studies + cross_references)

INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, w.original_word, w.transliteration, w.strongs_number, w.meaning, w.word_order
FROM verses v JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (3, 'γυναῖκα ἐπὶ μοιχείᾳ κατειλημμένην', 'gynaika epi moicheia kateilēmmenēn', 'G1135/G3430/G2638', 'Woman caught in adultery — pericope adulterae (7:53-8:11) absent from earliest MSS but ancient and likely authentic apostolic tradition.', 100),
  (4, 'ἐπ'' αὐτοφώρῳ', 'ep autophōrō', 'G1888', 'In the very act — autophōrōs: caught red-handed; legal terminology requiring eyewitness.', 101),
  (5, 'λιθάζειν', 'lithazein', 'G3036', 'To stone — Lev 20:10 / Deut 22:22 prescribed death for both adulterers; the absence of the man here is suspicious entrapment.', 102),
  (6, 'πειράζοντες', 'peirazontes', 'G3985', 'Testing/tempting — peirazō: legal trap; either contradict Moses (loses crowd) or contradict Roman law forbidding Jewish capital punishment.', 103),
  (6, 'ἔγραφεν εἰς τὴν γῆν', 'egraphen eis tēn gēn', 'G1125/G1093', 'Wrote on the ground — only NT instance of Jesus writing; possible Jer 17:13 echo (forsakers of God written in earth).', 104),
  (7, 'ὁ ἀναμάρτητος ὑμῶν πρῶτος', 'ho anamartētos hymōn prōtos', 'G361/G4413', 'The sinless one among you first — anamartētos: without sin; turns the trial upon the accusers; Deut 17:7 made witnesses cast first.', 105),
  (11, 'μηκέτι ἁμάρτανε', 'mēketi hamartane', 'G3371/G264', '"Sin no more" — present imperative; cessation, not absolute sinlessness; mercy with moral demand.', 106),
  (12, 'τὸ φῶς τοῦ κόσμου', 'to phōs tou kosmou', 'G5457/G2889', 'The light of the world — Tabernacles temple-court illumination as backdrop; cosmic-soteriological claim; cf. Isa 49:6.', 107),
  (12, 'ἕξει τὸ φῶς τῆς ζωῆς', 'hexei to phōs tēs zōēs', 'G5457/G2222', 'Will have the light of life — possessive future; light not just illuminates path but is the medium of life itself.', 108),
  (15, 'κατὰ τὴν σάρκα', 'kata tēn sarka', 'G2596/G4561', 'According to the flesh — superficial, externally-based judgment; condemned by Jesus (cf. 7:24).', 109),
  (16, 'ἡ κρίσις ἡ ἐμὴ ἀληθινή ἐστιν', 'hē krisis hē emē alēthinē estin', 'G2920/G228', 'My judgment is true — alēthinē: real, authentic; based on Father-Son partnership.', 110),
  (17, 'δύο ἀνθρώπων ἡ μαρτυρία ἀληθής ἐστιν', 'dyo anthrōpōn hē martyria alēthēs estin', 'G1417/G3141', 'The testimony of two men is true — Deut 19:15; Jesus and Father constitute the required two witnesses.', 111),
  (19, 'οὔτε ἐμὲ οἴδατε οὔτε τὸν πατέρα μου', 'oute eme oidate oute ton patera mou', 'G3777/G1492/G3962', 'You know neither me nor my Father — knowledge of Father comes only through the Son (cf. Matt 11:27; John 14:6-9).', 112),
  (20, 'ἐν τῷ γαζοφυλακίῳ', 'en tō gazophylakiō', 'G1049', 'In the treasury — Court of Women; 13 trumpet-shaped collection chests; central public location.', 113),
  (21, 'ἐν τῇ ἁμαρτίᾳ ὑμῶν ἀποθανεῖσθε', 'en tē hamartia hymōn apothaneisthe', 'G266/G599', 'You will die in your sin — singular hamartia: sin of unbelief in him; tragic finality of refusing the Light.', 114),
  (23, 'ὑμεῖς ἐκ τῶν κάτω... ἐγὼ ἐκ τῶν ἄνω', 'hymeis ek tōn katō... egō ek tōn anō', 'G2736/G507', 'You are from below... I am from above — origin contrast; not moral but ontological.', 115),
  (24, 'ἐγώ εἰμι', 'egō eimi', 'G1473/G1510', 'I AM (absolute) — without predicate; divine self-identification (cf. Exod 3:14; Isa 41:4 LXX); refusing this means dying in sin.', 116),
  (25, 'τὴν ἀρχὴν ὅ τι καὶ λαλῶ ὑμῖν', 'tēn archēn ho ti kai lalō hymin', 'G746/G2980', 'From the beginning what I have been saying — Jesus''s identity disclosed throughout his teaching.', 117),
  (29, 'οὐκ ἀφῆκέν με μόνον', 'ouk aphēken me monon', 'G863/G3441', 'Has not left me alone — the Father''s constant presence with the obedient Son; precedes Gethsemane abandonment.', 118),
  (29, 'τὰ ἀρεστὰ αὐτῷ', 'ta aresta autō', 'G701', 'The things pleasing to him — areston: pleasing; perfect filial obedience as proof of divine accompaniment.', 119),
  (31, 'μένητε ἐν τῷ λόγῳ τῷ ἐμῷ', 'menēte en tō logō tō emō', 'G3306/G3056', 'Abide in my word — menō: continuing; true discipleship is perseverance, not initial profession.', 120),
  (33, 'σπέρμα Ἀβραάμ ἐσμεν', 'sperma Abraam esmen', 'G4690/G11', 'Abraham''s seed we are — physical descent claim; Jesus distinguishes biological from spiritual sonship (cf. Rom 9:6-8).', 121),
  (37, 'ὁ λόγος ὁ ἐμὸς οὐ χωρεῖ ἐν ὑμῖν', 'ho logos ho emos ou chōrei en hymin', 'G3056/G5562', 'My word finds no place in you — chōreō: have room for; word seeks dwelling but rebuffed.', 122),
  (39, 'εἰ τέκνα τοῦ Ἀβραάμ ἐστε τὰ ἔργα τοῦ Ἀβραὰμ ἐποιεῖτε', 'ei tekna tou Abraam este ta erga tou Abraam epoieite', 'G5043/G2041', 'If Abraham''s children, you would do Abraham''s works — true paternity proven by character (cf. Matt 3:9).', 123),
  (41, 'οὐκ ἐκ πορνείας γεγεννήμεθα', 'ouk ek porneias gegennēmetha', 'G4202/G1080', 'We were not born of fornication — possible insinuation that Jesus''s birth was illegitimate (cf. Mark 6:3 "son of Mary").', 124),
  (42, 'ἀπὸ ἐμαυτοῦ οὐκ ἐλήλυθα', 'apo emautou ouk elēlytha', 'G1683/G2064', 'I have not come from myself — divine commissioning, not autonomous arrival.', 125),
  (44, 'ὑμεῖς ἐκ τοῦ πατρὸς τοῦ διαβόλου ἐστὲ', 'hymeis ek tou patros tou diabolou este', 'G3962/G1228', 'You are of your father the devil — startling spiritual genealogy; opposition to Christ reveals Satanic descent.', 126),
  (44, 'ἀνθρωποκτόνος', 'anthrōpoktonos', 'G443', 'Manslayer/murderer — anthrōpos + kteinō; the devil''s nature from beginning (Gen 3:4; 4:8); cf. 1 John 3:8,15.', 127),
  (44, 'οὐκ ἔστηκεν ἐν τῇ ἀληθείᾳ', 'ouk estēken en tē alētheia', 'G2476/G225', 'Did not stand in the truth — perfect: never stood; ontological fall before any deception.', 128),
  (45, 'ὅτι τὴν ἀλήθειαν λέγω οὐ πιστεύετέ μοι', 'hoti tēn alētheian legō ou pisteuete moi', 'G225/G3004/G4100', 'Because I tell the truth you do not believe me — paradoxical reaction; truth-telling repels those of the lie-father.', 129),
  (46, 'τίς ἐξ ὑμῶν ἐλέγχει με περὶ ἁμαρτίας', 'tis ex hymōn elenchei me peri hamartias', 'G1651/G266', 'Who of you convicts me of sin? — Jesus''s sinlessness challenge; only the perfect can issue this.', 130),
  (48, 'Σαμαρίτης εἶ σὺ καὶ δαιμόνιον ἔχεις', 'Samaritēs ei sy kai daimonion echeis', 'G4541/G1140', 'You are a Samaritan and have a demon — double slander; ethnic + spiritual; Jesus answers the second only.', 131),
  (51, 'τὸν ἐμὸν λόγον τηρήσῃ', 'ton emon logon tērēsē', 'G3056/G5083', 'Keeps my word — tēreō: guard, observe; believer never sees death (spiritual/eternal); promise to perseverers.', 132),
  (53, 'μὴ σὺ μείζων εἶ τοῦ πατρὸς ἡμῶν Ἀβραάμ', 'mē sy meizōn ei tou patros hēmōn Abraam', 'G3187/G3962', 'Are you greater than our father Abraham? — implicit answer is yes (cf. Heb 7:7); they read the question rightly.', 133),
  (56, 'ἠγαλλιάσατο ἵνα ἴδῃ τὴν ἡμέραν τὴν ἐμήν', 'ēgalliasato hina idē tēn hēmeran tēn emēn', 'G21/G2250', 'Rejoiced to see my day — Abraham foresaw the day of Christ; possible reference to Gen 22 (Isaac typology).', 134),
  (57, 'πεντήκοντα ἔτη οὔπω ἔχεις', 'pentēkonta etē oupō echeis', 'G4004/G2094', 'Not yet 50 years old — round number for "not even old enough to have known antiquity"; some have used to date Jesus mid-30s.', 135),
  (58, 'πρὶν Ἀβραὰμ γενέσθαι ἐγὼ εἰμί', 'prin Abraam genesthai egō eimi', 'G4250/G1096/G1473/G1510', 'Before Abraham came into being I AM — eternal pre-existence; absolute egō eimi; deity claim crystal clear.', 136),
  (59, 'ἦραν λίθους ἵνα βάλωσιν ἐπ'' αὐτόν', 'ēran lithous hina balōsin ep auton', 'G142/G3037/G906', 'Took up stones to throw at him — Lev 24:16 prescribes stoning for blasphemy; they understood his claim correctly.', 137)
) AS w(verse_number, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'John' AND c.chapter_number = 8 AND v.verse_number = w.verse_number
ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;

